    "summary": "CONFIRM — all six term renderings approved",
    "content": "**CONFIRM**\n\nAll six rendering decisions are sound from an existentialist perspective:\n\n1. **道 → \"the Way\"**: Correct. Neutral enough to carry the author's structural usage without importing Daoist metaphysical baggage.\n2. **德 split**: Essential. The whole passage demonstrates how 德 undergoes a transformation — from \"virtue\" (the received metaphysical sense in the Laozi) to \"character\" (the author's reconstructed, bottom-up sense). The split enacts in translation exactly what the passage argues.\n3. **仁 → \"humaneness\"**: Right choice. \"Benevolence\" implies top-down bestowal; \"humaneness\" keeps the connection to what-it-is-to-be-human, which is precisely what the passage puts under pressure (the property-to-definition reversal).\n4. **义 → \"rightness\"**: Correct. \"Righteousness\" carries moral judgment; \"rightness\" stays closer to the author's usage as motivational disposition — the driving force connecting feeling to action.\n5. **礼 → \"ritual conduct\"**: Good. \"Conduct\" preserves the behavioral/phenomenal dimension that the passage depends on. \"Rites\" or \"propriety\" would be too abstract.\n6. **现象X → \"phenomenal X\"**: Consistent and necessary. The \"phenomenal\" prefix is the author's own philosophical move — marking the difference between lived experience and its metaphysical reification.\n\nNo objections."
  }
